<Link id="l00027" /><CodeLine lineNumber="27"><Highlight kind="comment">/// MappedBlockStream represents data stored in an MSF file into chunks of a</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00028" /><CodeLine lineNumber="28"><Highlight kind="comment">/// particular size (called the Block Size), and whose chunks may not be</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00029" /><CodeLine lineNumber="29"><Highlight kind="comment">/// necessarily contiguous.  The arrangement of these chunks MSF the file</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00030" /><CodeLine lineNumber="30"><Highlight kind="comment">/// is described by some other metadata contained within the MSF file.  In</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00031" /><CodeLine lineNumber="31"><Highlight kind="comment">/// the case of a standard MSF Stream, the layout of the stream&#39;s blocks</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00032" /><CodeLine lineNumber="32"><Highlight kind="comment">/// is described by the MSF &quot;directory&quot;, but in the case of the directory</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00033" /><CodeLine lineNumber="33"><Highlight kind="comment">/// itself, the layout is described by an array at a fixed location within</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00034" /><CodeLine lineNumber="34"><Highlight kind="comment">/// the MSF.  MappedBlockStream provides methods for reading from and writing</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00035" /><CodeLine lineNumber="35"><Highlight kind="comment">/// to one of these streams transparently, as if it were a contiguous sequence</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00036" /><CodeLine lineNumber="36"><Highlight kind="comment">/// of bytes.</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>

<Link id="l00094" /><CodeLine lineNumber="94"><Highlight kind="normal">  </Highlight><Highlight kind="comment">// We just store the allocator by reference.  We use this to allocate</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00095" /><CodeLine lineNumber="95"><Highlight kind="normal">  </Highlight><Highlight kind="comment">// contiguous memory for things like arrays or strings that cross a block</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00096" /><CodeLine lineNumber="96"><Highlight kind="normal">  </Highlight><Highlight kind="comment">// boundary, and this memory is expected to outlive the stream.  For example,</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00097" /><CodeLine lineNumber="97"><Highlight kind="normal">  </Highlight><Highlight kind="comment">// someone could create a stream, read some stuff, then close the stream, and</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00098" /><CodeLine lineNumber="98"><Highlight kind="normal">  </Highlight><Highlight kind="comment">// we would like outstanding references to fields to remain valid since the</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00099" /><CodeLine lineNumber="99"><Highlight kind="normal">  </Highlight><Highlight kind="comment">// entire file is mapped anyway.  Because of that, the user must supply the</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00100" /><CodeLine lineNumber="100"><Highlight kind="normal">  </Highlight><Highlight kind="comment">// allocator to allocate broken records from.</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
